Definition 5.6. Let $\mathcal{B}$,$\mathcal{C}$,$\mathcal{D}$ be weak cofibration categories and let $(-)\otimes(-):\mathcal{B}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be a bifunctor. The bifunctor $\otimes$ is called a weak left Quillen bifunctor if $\otimes$ commutes with finite colimits in every variable separately, and for every cofibration $j:X\to Y$ in $\mathcal{B}$ and every cofibration $i:L\to K$ in $\mathcal{C}$ the induced map $X\otimes K\coprod_{X\otimes L}Y\otimes L\to Y\otimes K$ is a cofibration (in $\mathcal{D}$), which is acyclic if either $i$ or $j$ is.
Definition 4.2. Let $\mathcal{B}$,$\mathcal{C}$,$\mathcal{D}$ be categories and let $(-)\otimes(-):\mathcal{B}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be a bifunctor. We have a naturally induced prolongation of $\otimes$ to a bifunctor (which we also denote by $\otimes$) $(-)\otimes(-):\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{B})\times\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal% {C})\to\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{D}).$ If $B=\{B_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ is an object in $\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{B})$ and $C=\{C_{j}\}_{j\in J}$ is an object in $\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})$, then $B\otimes C$ is the object in $\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{D})$ given by the diagram $\{B_{i}\otimes C_{j}\}_{(i,j)\in I\times J}.$
Definition 2.8. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category with finite colimits and let $M$ be a class of morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$. 1. We denote by $\textup{R}(M)$ the class of morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$ that are retracts of morphisms in $M$. Note that $\textup{R}(\textup{R}(M))=\textup{R}(M)$. 2. We denote by $M^{\perp}$ (resp. ${}^{\perp}M$) the class of morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$ having the right (resp. left) lifting property with respect to all the morphisms in $M$. 3. We denote by $\operatorname{Lw}^{\cong}(M)$ the class of morphisms in $\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})$ that are isomorphic to a morphism that comes from a natural transformation which is a levelwise $M$-map. 4. We denote by $\operatorname{coSp}^{\cong}(M)$ the class of morphisms in $\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})$ that are isomorphic to a morphism that comes from a natural transformation which is a cospecial $M$-map.
Definition 2.5. Let $T$ be a poset. Then we view $T$ as a category which has a single morphism $u\to v$ iff $u\leq v$. Note that this convention is the opposite of that used in [BaSc1].
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{B}$,$\mathcal{C}$,$\mathcal{D}$ be categories. An adjunction of two variables from $\mathcal{B}\times\mathcal{C}$ to $\mathcal{D}$ is a quintuple $(\otimes,\operatorname{Hom}_{r},\operatorname{Hom}_{l},\phi_{r},\phi_{l})$, where $(-)\otimes(-):\mathcal{B}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$, $\operatorname{Hom}_{r}(-,-):\mathcal{C}^{op}\times\mathcal{D}\to\mathcal{B}$, $\operatorname{Hom}_{l}(-,-):\mathcal{B}^{op}\times\mathcal{D}\to\mathcal{C}$ are bifunctors, and $\phi_{r},\phi_{l}$ are natural isomorphisms $\phi_{r}:\mathcal{D}(B\otimes C,D)\xrightarrow{\cong}\mathcal{B}(B,% \operatorname{Hom}_{r}(C,D)),$ $\phi_{l}:\mathcal{D}(B\otimes C,D)\xrightarrow{\cong}\mathcal{C}(C,% \operatorname{Hom}_{l}(B,D)).$
Definition 2.7. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category with finite colimits, $M$ a class of morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$, $I$ a small category, and $F:X\to Y$ a morphism in $\mathcal{C}^{I}$. Then: 1. The map $F$ will be called a level-wise $M$-map, if for every $i\in I$ the morphism $X_{i}\to Y_{i}$ is in $M$. We will denote this by $F\in\operatorname{Lw}(M)$. 2. The map $F$ will be called a cospecial $M$-map, if $I$ is a cofinite poset and for every $t\in I$ the natural map $X_{t}\coprod_{\mathop{\operatorname{colim}}_{s<t}X_{s}}\mathop{\operatorname{% colim}}_{s<t}Y_{s}\to Y_{t}$ is in $M$. We will denote this by $F\in\operatorname{coSp}(M)$.
Definition 2.13. A weak cofibration category is a category ${\mathcal{C}}$ with an additional structure of two subcategories ${\mathcal{C}of},{\mathcal{W}}\subseteq{\mathcal{C}}$ that contain all the isomorphisms such that the following conditions are satisfied: 1. ${\mathcal{C}}$ has all finite limits. 2. ${\mathcal{W}}$ has the two out of three property. 3. The subcategories ${\mathcal{C}of}$ and ${\mathcal{C}of}\cap{\mathcal{W}}$ are closed under cobase change. 4. Every map $A\to B$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ can be factored as $A\xrightarrow{f}C\xrightarrow{g}B$, where $f$ is in ${\mathcal{C}of}$ and $g$ is in ${\mathcal{W}}$. The maps in ${\mathcal{C}of}$ are called cofibrations, and the maps in ${\mathcal{W}}$ are called weak equivalences.
Definition 5.13. Let $(\mathcal{M},\otimes,I)$ be a weak cofibration category which is also a monoidal category. We will say that $\mathcal{M}$, with this structure, is a monoidal weak cofibration category if the following conditions are satisfied: 1. $\otimes:\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{M}$ be a weak left Quillen bifunctor (see 5.6). 2. $I$ is a cofibrant object in $\mathcal{M}$.
Definition 4.6. Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a monoidal category with finite colimits and let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category with finite colimits. Let $\otimes$ be a left action of $\mathcal{M}$ on $\mathcal{C}$. We will say that this action is weakly closed if $\otimes$ commutes with finite colimits in each variable separately.
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category. The category $\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})$ has as objects all diagrams in $\mathcal{C}$ of the form $I\to\mathcal{C}$ such that $I$ is small and filtered. The morphisms are defined by the formula $\operatorname{Hom}_{\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})}(X,Y):=\lim_{s}\mathop{% \operatorname{colim}}_{t}\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(X_{s},Y_{t}).$ Composition of morphisms is defined in the obvious way.
Definition 5.11. Let $(\mathcal{M},\otimes,I)$ be a monoidal category which is also an almost model category. We will say that $\mathcal{M}$, with this structure, is a monoidal almost model category if the following conditions are satisfied: 1. $\otimes:\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{M}$ be a left Quillen bifunctor (see Definition 5.1). 2. $I$ is a cofibrant object in $\mathcal{M}$. We denote the two variable adjunction of $\otimes$ by $(\otimes,\operatorname{Hom},\operatorname{Hom})$. Note that $\operatorname{Hom}(-,-):\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{C})^{op}\times% \operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{M})\to\operatorname{Ind}(\mathcal{M}).$
Definition 4.4. Let $(\mathcal{M},\otimes,I)$ be a monoidal category (see for example [Lur, Section A.1.3]) with finite colimits. We will say that $\mathcal{M}$ is weakly closed if $\otimes$ commutes with finite colimits in each variable separately.
Definition 5.16. Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a monoidal weak cofibration category, and let $\mathcal{C}$ be a weak cofibration category which is also tensored over $\mathcal{M}$. We say that $\mathcal{C}$, with this structure, is an $\mathcal{M}$-enriched weak cofibration category if $(-)\otimes(-):\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$ is a weak left Quillen bifunctor (See Definition 5.6).
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an almost model category or a weak cofibration category. Then $\mathcal{C}$ is called left proper if for every pushout square of the form $\xymatrix{A\ar[d]^{i}\ar[r]^{f}&B\ar[d]^{j}\\ C\ar[r]&D}$ such that $f$ is a cofibration and $i$ is a weak equivalence, the map $j$ is a weak equivalence.
Definition 5.2. Let $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be a functor between two almost model categories. Then $F$ is called a left Quillen functor if $F$ is a left adjoint and $F$ preserves cofibrations and trivial cofibrations.
Definition 3.1. The $K$-theory space $K(C)$ of the stable $\infty$-category $C$ is defined to be the loop space $\Omega|S_{\bullet}^{\sim}(C)|$, where we take a zero object of $C$ as base point.
Definition 3.3. Let $X\colon\Delta^{\mathrm{op}}\to C$, $[n]\mapsto X_{n}$, be a simplicial object in an $\infty$-category $C$. Then the edgewise subdivision $E(X)$ is defined to be the simplicial object $X\circ\iota^{\mathrm{op}}$, where $\iota\colon\Delta\to\Delta$ is the endofunctor defined by $[n]\mapsto[n]^{\mathrm{op}}*[n]$.
Definition 3.4. For $C$ a stable $\infty$-category with duality we let the Grothendieck-Witt space $\mathrm{GW}(C)$ of $C$ be the homotopy fiber of the composition $|(S_{\bullet}^{e,\sim}(C))_{h}|\to|S_{\bullet}^{e,\sim}(C)|\to|S_{\bullet}^{% \sim}(C)|.$
Definition 5.9. For $n\in{\mathbb{N}}$ the abelian group $\mathrm{GW}_{n}(C):=\pi_{n}\mathrm{GW}(C)$ is called the $n$-th Grothendieck-Witt group of the stable $\infty$-category $C$ with duality. In particular the group $\mathrm{GW}_{0}(C)$ is called the Grothendieck-Witt group of $C$.
Definition 4.5. Let $n\in\mathds{N}$. An operation $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$ is called homogeneous of degree $n$ if for every $R$-module $M$ we have $F_{R[T]}\bigl{(}T\cdot\operatorname{id}_{M[T]}\bigr{)}=T^{n}\cdot\operatorname% {id}_{F_{R[T]}(M[T])}.$ Let $[\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}},\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}]_{n}\subseteq[% \operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}},\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}]$ denote the full subcategory of operations which are homogeneous of degree $n$.
Definition 5.4. Let $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}\to\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}$ be an operation which is homogeneous of degree $n$. Let $F^{\prime}$ and $L_{F}$ be defined as in Definition 5.2. Let $\sigma\in\Sigma_{n}$ be a permutation and let $M_{1},\dotsc,M_{n}$ be a sequence of $R$-modules. There is an isomorphism $\tilde{\sigma}:M_{1}\oplus\dots\oplus M_{n}\to M_{\sigma(1)}\oplus\dots\oplus M% _{\sigma(n)}$ characterized by $\tilde{\sigma}\circ\iota_{\sigma(i)}=\iota_{i}$, and therefore an isomorphism (denoted by the same symbol) $\tilde{\sigma}:F^{\prime}_{R}(M_{1},\dotsc,M_{n})\to F^{\prime}_{R}(M_{\sigma(% 1)},\dotsc,M_{\sigma(n)}).$ It is easily checked that this restricts to an isomorphism $\tilde{\sigma}:(L_{F})_{R}(M_{1},\dotsc,M_{n})\to(L_{F})_{R}(M_{\sigma(1)},% \dotsc,M_{\sigma(n)}).$ Basically, this is because $T_{1}\cdot\dots\cdot T_{n}$ is a symmetric polynomial. In particular, for every $R$-module $M$, the symmetric group $\Sigma_{n}$ acts from the right on the $R$-module $(L_{F})_{R}(M,\dotsc,M)$. In particular, we obtain a right $k[\Sigma_{n}]$-module structure on the $k$-module $(L_{F})_{k}(k,\dotsc,k)$. This right $k[\Sigma_{n}]$-module will be denoted by $\mathcal{V}_{F}$. Every morphism of operations $F\to G$ restricts to a morphism of operations $L_{F}\to L_{G}$ and then to a morphism of right $k[\Sigma_{n}]$-modules $\mathcal{V}_{F}\to\mathcal{V}_{G}$. This defines a functor $[\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}},\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}]_{n}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_% {\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}\bigl{(}k[\Sigma_{n}]\bigr{)},\quad F\mapsto% \mathcal{V}_{F}.$
Definition 4.2. If $G$ is a commutative monoid, let us denote by $\operatorname{\mathsf{gr}}_{G}\!\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}(R)$ the category of $G$-graded $R$-modules. If $M=\bigoplus_{g\in G}M_{g}$ is a graded $R$-module and $R\to S$ is a $k$-homomorphism, we endow $M\otimes_{R}S$ with the grading $M\otimes_{R}S=\bigoplus_{g\in G}M_{g}\otimes_{R}S$. This defines a pseudofunctor $\operatorname{\mathsf{gr}}_{G}\!\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}:\operatorname{% \mathsf{CAlg}}(k)\to\operatorname{\mathsf{CAT}}$ together with a forgetful operation $\operatorname{\mathsf{gr}}_{G}\!\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}\to\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}$.
Definition 4.9. Let us call an operation $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}\to\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}$ bounded if there is some $n\in\mathds{N}$ such that $F_{m}=0$ for all $m>n$. We get a full subcategory $[\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}},\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}]_{\mathrm{bounded}}$ of $[\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}},\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}]$.
Definition 3.1. Let $k$ be a commutative ring. An operation $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}\to\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}$ is called linear if for every commutative $k$-algebra $R$ the functor $F_{R}:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}(R)\to% \operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}(R)$ is $R$-linear. This defines a full subcategory $[\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}},\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}]_{1}\subseteq[\operatorname{\mathsf% {Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}},\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname% {\mathsf{fg}}}].$ It contains the identity operation and is closed under composition, therefore may be regarded as a monoidal $k$-linear category. The category $[\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fp}}},\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fp}}}]_{1}$ is defined in a similar way.
Definition 2.1. Let $k$ be a commutative ring. An operation $\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$ over $k$ is a family of functors $F_{R}:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}(R)\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}(R),$ defined for every commutative $k$-algebra $R$, equipped with isomorphisms of $S$-modules $\theta_{f}(M):F_{R}(M)\otimes_{R}S\xrightarrow{\,\smash{\raisebox{-1.29pt}{$% \scriptstyle\sim$}}\,}F_{S}(M\otimes_{R}S),$ for each $k$-homomorphism $f:R\to S$, natural in $M\in\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}(R)$, such that the following two coherence conditions are satisfied: the diagram $\tikzcd[rowsep=25pt]F_{R}(M)\otimes_{R}R\ar{rr}{\theta_{\operatorname{id}_{R}}% (M)}&&F_{R}(M\otimes_{R}R)\\ &F_{R}(M)\ar{ur}[swap]{\cong}\ar{ul}{\cong}&$ commutes, and for all $k$-homomorphisms $f:R\to S$, $g:S\to T$ the diagram $\tikzcd[columnsep=55pt,rowsep=25pt](F_{R}(M)\otimes_{R}S)\otimes_{S}T\ar{r}{% \theta_{f}(M)\otimes_{S}T}\ar{d}[swap]{\cong}&F_{S}(M\otimes_{R}S)\otimes_{S}T% \ar{r}{\theta_{g}(M\otimes_{R}S)}&F_{T}((M\otimes_{R}S)\otimes_{S}T)\ar{d}{% \cong}\\ F_{R}(M)\otimes_{R}T\ar{rr}{\theta_{g\circ f}(M)}&&F_{T}(M\otimes_{R}T)$ commutes. A morphism of operations $(F,\theta)\to(F^{\prime},\theta^{\prime})$ is defined as a family of morphisms of functors $\alpha_{R}:F_{R}\to F^{\prime}_{R}$, defined for every commutative $k$-algebra $R$, such that for all $k$-homomorphisms $f:R\to S$ and all $R$-modules $M$ the diagram $\tikzcd[columnsep=40pt,rowsep=25pt]F_{R}(M)\otimes_{R}S\ar{r}{\theta_{f}(M)}% \ar{d}[swap]{\alpha_{R}(M)\otimes S}&F_{S}(M\otimes_{R}S)\ar{d}{\alpha_{S}(M% \otimes_{R}S)}\\ F^{\prime}_{R}(M)\otimes_{R}S\ar{r}{\theta^{\prime}_{f}(M)}&F^{\prime}_{S}(M% \otimes_{R}S)$ commutes. Usually we will suppress the isomorphisms $\theta_{f}$ from the notation. Operations of the form $\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}\to\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}$ and $\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fp}}}\to\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fp}}}$ over $k$ are defined in a similar way. For fixed $n\in\mathds{N}$, operations with $n$ arguments $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}^{n}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$ are defined in a similar way, including the variants with $\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}$ and $\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fp}}}$. Here, we require natural isomorphisms $F_{R}(M_{1},\dotsc,M_{n})\otimes_{R}S\xrightarrow{\,\smash{\raisebox{-1.29pt}{% $\scriptstyle\sim$}}\,}F_{S}(M_{1}\otimes_{R}S,\dotsc,M_{n}\otimes_{R}S).$
Definition 3.6. Let $k$ be a commutative ring and $n\in\mathds{N}$. An operation with $n$ arguments $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}^{n}\to\operatorname% {\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}$ will be called multilinear if it is linear in each variable. This means that for every index $1\leq i\leq n$ and every family of finitely generated $R$-modules $M_{1},\dotsc,M_{i-1},M_{i+1},\dotsc,M_{n}$ the functor $F_{R}(M_{1},\dotsc,M_{i-1},\square,M_{i+1},\dotsc,M_{n}):\operatorname{\mathsf% {Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}(R)\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{% \operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}(R)$ is $R$-linear. This defines a full subcategory $[\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}^{n},\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}]_{1,\dotsc,1}\subseteq[% \operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}^{n},\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}].$ For $n=1$ we recover $[\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}},\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}]_{1}$.
Definition 5.5. Conversely, let $V$ be a finitely generated right $k[\Sigma_{n}]$-module. We define the corresponding Schur operation by $\SS_{V}:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}\to% \operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}},\,M\mapsto V\otimes_{% k[\Sigma_{n}]}M^{\otimes n},$ equipped with the evident base change isomorphisms. Here, $\Sigma_{n}$ acts from the left on $M^{\otimes n}$ by $\sigma\cdot(m_{1}\otimes\dots\otimes m_{n})\coloneqq m_{\sigma^{-1}(1)}\otimes% \dots\otimes m_{\sigma^{-1}(n)}.$ Observe that $\SS_{V}$ is homogeneous of degree $n$, and that every homomorphism of right $k[\Sigma_{n}]$-modules $V\to W$ induces a morphism $\SS_{V}\to\SS_{W}$ of operations. This defines a functor $\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}\bigl{(}k[\Sigma_{n}]% \bigr{)}\to[\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}},% \operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}]_{n},\quad V\mapsto% \SS_{V}.$
Definition 5.2. Let $n\in\mathds{N}$. Let $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$ be an operation which is homogeneous of degree $n$. We define the operation $F^{\prime}:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}^{n}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$ by $F^{\prime}_{R}(M_{1},\dotsc,M_{n})\coloneqq F_{R}(M_{1}\oplus\dots\oplus M_{n}),$ equipped with the evident base change isomorphisms. We now apply Remark 5.1 and construct a decomposition $F^{\prime}\cong\bigoplus_{i_{1},\dotsc,i_{n}}F^{\prime}_{i_{1},\dotsc,i_{n}}$ into homogeneous operations. Here, the only non-trivial operations are those with $i_{1}+\dots+i_{n}=n$; this is because the associated $\mathds{N}$-grading on $F^{\prime}_{R}(M_{1},\dotsc,M_{n})=F_{R}(M_{1}\oplus\dots\oplus M_{n})$ is induced by the trivial $\mathds{N}$-grading on $M_{1}\oplus\dots\oplus M_{n}$ concentrated in degree $1$ and $F$ is assumed to be homogeneous of degree $n$. In particular, we define the operation $L_{F}\coloneqq F^{\prime}_{1,\dotsc,1}:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}^{n}\to% \operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$ and call $L_{F}$ the linearization of $F$. Explicitly, an element $u\in F_{R}(M_{1}\oplus\dots\oplus M_{n})$ belongs to $(L_{F})_{R}(M_{1},\dotsc,M_{n})$ if and only if the endomorphism $F_{R}(M_{1}\oplus\dots\oplus M_{n})\bigl{[}T_{1},\dotsc,T_{n}\bigr{]}\to F_{R}% (M_{1}\oplus\dots\oplus M_{n})\bigl{[}T_{1},\dotsc,T_{n}\bigr{]}$ which is induced by the endomorphism $\bigoplus_{i=1}^{n}T_{i}\cdot\operatorname{id}_{M_{i}[T_{1},\dotsc,T_{n}]}$ maps $u\cdot 1$ to $u\cdot T_{1}\cdots T_{n}$. We make similar definitions for operations $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}\to\operatorname{% \mathsf{Mod}}_{\operatorname{\mathsf{fg}}}$.
Definition 4.4. Let $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$ be an operation. By Corollary 4.3, $F$ lifts to an operation $\operatorname{\mathsf{gr}}_{\mathds{N}}\!\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}\to% \operatorname{\mathsf{gr}}_{\mathds{N}}\!\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$. Let us compose this with the operation $\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{gr}}_{\mathds{N}}\!% \operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$ which equips every module with the trivial grading concentrated in degree $1$. Thus, we obtain a family of operations $F_{n}:\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{Mod}}$ with an isomorphism of operations $\bigoplus_{n\in\mathds{N}}F_{n}\xrightarrow{\,\smash{\raisebox{-1.29pt}{$% \scriptstyle\sim$}}\,}F.$ We call $F_{n}$ the homogeneous component of degree $n$ of $F$. Specifically, if $M$ is some $R$-module, then $(F_{n})_{R}(M)$ consists of those elements $u\in F_{R}(M)$ such that $F_{R[T]}\bigl{(}T\cdot\operatorname{id}_{M[T]}\bigr{)}$ maps $u\cdot 1$ to $u\cdot T^{n}\in F_{R}(M)[T]$ (using the identification $F_{R[T]}(M[T])\cong F_{R}(M)[T]$).
Definition 5.3 (Complexity of functors). Let $\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D}$ be two categories with complexity functions, $C_{\mathcal{C}},C_{\mathcal{D}}$, and let $F:\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ be a functor. We define the complexity, $c(F):\mathbb{N}\rightarrow\mathbb{N}$ by $c(F)(n)=\sup\left\{C_{\mathcal{D}}(D)\,\,|\,\,I\text{ a finite directed graph}% ,\,D\in\mathcal{C}^{I},\,C_{\mathcal{C}}(D)\leq n\right\}.$
Definition 2.10. The cost of the computation $(D_{0},\dots,D_{s})$ is the the number of steps plus the cost of the initial diagram $D_{0}$ consisting of basic morphisms, that is $c(D_{0},\dots,D_{s})=s+\sum_{f\in\operatorname{edges}(I_{0})}c_{0}(D_{0}(f)).$
Definition 2.7. A mixed computation is a finite sequence $(D_{0},\dots,D_{s})$ of diagrams with $D_{i}:I_{i}\to U(\mathcal{C})$, where $D_{0}$ consists only of morphisms in $\mathcal{A}$, and for each $i=1,\dots,s$, $D_{i}$ is obtained from $D_{i-1}$ by adding either the limit of a subdiagram, with the corresponding cone morphisms or colimit of a subdiagram with the corresponding cocone morphisms.
Definition 2.11. The limit (resp. colimit, resp. mixed) complexity $C(D)=C_{\mathcal{C},\mathcal{A}}(D)$, short for $C^{\operatorname{lim}}_{\mathcal{C},\mathcal{A},c}(D)$ (resp., $C^{\operatorname{colim}}_{\mathcal{C},\mathcal{A},c}(D)$, resp., $C^{\operatorname{mixed}}_{\mathcal{C},\mathcal{A},c}(D)$), of a diagram $D$ in a category $\mathcal{C}$ is the cost of the limit (resp., colimit, resp. mixed) computation using basic morphisms $\mathcal{A}$, that has the smallest cost among all such computations that compute $D$. For a morphism $f:X\rightarrow Y$ in $\mathcal{C}$, the complexity $C(f)$ of $f$ is the complexity of the corresponding diagram mapping two objects and a single morphism $X\raisebox{-0.853583pt}{\scalebox{0.85}{$\,\xrightarrow{f}\,$}}Y$. For an object $X$ in $\mathcal{C}$, the complexity $C(X)$ of $X$ is the complexity of the diagram with one object, $X$.
Definition 2.1. Let, $\mathcal{C}$ be a category, $\mathcal{A}\subset\mathrm{Mor}(\mathcal{C})$. A limit computation (respectively, a colimit computation) in $\mathcal{C}$ is a finite sequence of diagrams $(D_{0},\dots,D_{s})$, with $D_{i}:I_{i}\to U(\mathcal{C})$, where: (i) $D_{0}$ consists only of morphisms in $\mathcal{A}$, the basic morphisms. (ii) For each $i=1,\dots,s$, $D_{i}$ is obtained from $D_{i-1}$ by adding a limit or colimit cone of a subdiagram. More precisely, there is a sub-diagram $D_{i-1}|_{J_{i}}$ of $D_{i-1}$ and an object $L_{i}$ which is a limit (resp $C_{i}$ which is a colimit) of $D_{i-1}|_{J_{i}}$ such that the difference between $D_{i}$ and $D_{i-1}$ are $L_{i}$ and the limit cone morphisms out of $L_{i}$ (resp. $C_{i}$ and the colimit cocone morphisms into $C_{i}$). (iii) (Constructivity) If a limit $L_{i}=\lim D_{i-1}|_{J_{i}}$ (resp., colimit $C_{i}$) produced in the $i$th step of the computation is used again in the subdiagram $D_{j-1}|_{J_{j}}$ used at the $j$th step of the computation, then $J_{i}\subset J_{j}$, i.e. the subdiagram that produced $L_{i}$ (resp., $C_{i}$) must be a sub-diagram of $D_{i-1}|_{J_{j}}$. The computation $(D_{0},\dots,D_{s})$ is said to compute a diagram $D$, if $D$ is isomorphic to (a not necessarily full) subdiagram of $D_{s}$. In particular, an object in $\mathcal{C}$ is computed by $(D_{0},\dots,D_{s})$ if an object isomorphic to it appears in $D_{s}$.
Definition 2.7. A rack is involutary if the axiom $x\rhd(x\rhd y)$ is satisfied.
Definition 6.1. Let $K$ be a knot with knot quandle $\mathrm{Q}K$. The Alexander–Beck module of $K$ is the $\mathrm{Q}K$-module $\Omega_{\mathrm{Q}K}(\mathrm{Q}K)$.
Definition 2.2. An abelian rack is an abelian group object in the category $\mathbf{R}$ of racks, or equivalently, a rack object in abelian groups.
Definition 4.1. The objects in $\operatorname{Ab}(\mathbf{T}_{X})$ are the $X$-modules in the sense of Beck [1].
Definition. Let $K$ be a knot with knot quandle $\mathrm{Q}K$. The Alexander–Beck module of $K$ is the value of the left adjoint of the forgetful functor from $\mathrm{Q}K$-modules to quandles over $\mathrm{Q}K$ at the terminal object.
Definition 4.4. The left adjoint $\Omega_{X}\colon\mathbf{T}_{X}\longrightarrow\operatorname{Ab}(\mathbf{T}_{X}).$ to the forgetful functor $\operatorname{Ab}(\mathbf{T}_{X})\to\mathbf{T}_{X}$ is the (relative) abelianization functor.
Definition 2.5. A quandle is a rack such that its canonical automorphism is the identity.
Definition 2.1. A rack $(R,\rhd)$ is a set $R$ together with a binary operation $\rhd$ such that all left multiplications $R\longrightarrow R,\,y\longmapsto x\rhd y$ are automorphisms, i.e. they are bijective and satisfy $x\rhd(y\rhd z)=(x\rhd y)\rhd(x\rhd z)$ for all $x$, $y$, and $z$.
Definition 1.1. If $\mathbf{C}$ is a category with finite products, an abelian group object in $\mathbf{C}$ is an object $M$ together with operations $e\colon\star\to M$ (the unit), $i\colon M\to M$ (the inverse), and $a\colon M\times M\to M$ (the addition) such that, writing $e^{\prime}$ for the composition of $e$ with the unique map $M\to\star$, the four diagrams $\xymatrix{M\times M\times M\ar[r]^{-}{\operatorname{id}\times a}\ar[d]_{a% \times\operatorname{id}}&M\times M\ar[d]^{a}\\ M\times M\ar[r]_{a}&M}\hskip 10.0pt\xymatrix{M\times M\ar[dr]_{a}\ar[rr]^{(% \operatorname{pr}_{2},\operatorname{pr}_{1})}&&M\times M\ar[dl]^{a}\\ &M&}$ $\xymatrix{M\ar[r]^{-}{(\operatorname{id},e^{\prime})}\ar[dr]_{\operatorname{id% }}&M\times M\ar[d]|a&M\ar[l]_{-}{(e^{\prime},\operatorname{id})}\ar[dl]^{% \operatorname{id}}\\ &M&}\hskip 10.0pt\xymatrix{M\ar[r]^{-}{(\operatorname{id},i)}\ar[dr]_{e^{% \prime}}&M\times M\ar[d]|a&M\ar[l]_{-}{(i,\operatorname{id})}\ar[dl]^{e^{% \prime}}\\ &M&}$ commute.
Definition 2.1. A nonzero object $M$ in an abelian category ${\cal A}$ is monoform if for every nonzero subobject $N\leq M$ there are no nonzero common subobjects of both $M$ and $M/N$.
Definition 2.3. An object $M\neq 0$ in an abelian category ${\cal A}$ is premonoform if it contains no nontrivial quotient as a subobject, meaning that there is no injection from $M/N$ to $M$, for any nonzero proper subobject $N\leq M$.
Definition 3.1. Let ${\cal A}$ be an abelian category and ${\cal B}$ a full subcategory of ${\cal A}$. Consider (1) for any exact sequence $0\rightarrow N\rightarrow M$, $M\in{\cal B}$ implies $N\in{\cal B}$; (1’) dually for any exact sequence $M\rightarrow N^{\prime}\rightarrow 0$, $M\in{\cal B}$ implies $N^{\prime}\in{\cal B}$; (2) for any exact sequence $0\rightarrow N\rightarrow M\rightarrow N^{\prime}\rightarrow 0$, that $N,N^{\prime}\in{\cal B}$ implies $M\in{\cal B}$, then ${\cal B}$ is called a nullity class if it satisfies (1’) and (2), and ${\cal B}$ is called a Serre subcategory if it is an abelian subcategory of ${\cal A}$ and satisfies (1), (1’) and (2).
Definition 5.3. Let ${\cal A}$ be an abelian category and ${\mathrm{Spec}}{\cal A}$ its spectrum (either a set or a class), $\Phi\subseteq{\mathrm{Spec}}{\cal A}$ a subclass. The subclass $\Phi$ is closed if for every $\overline{M}\in\Phi$, ${\mathrm{Supp}}M\subseteq\Phi$. The subclass $\Phi$ is extension closed if whenever there is a short exact sequence $0\rightarrow M\rightarrow X\rightarrow N\rightarrow 0,$ such that ${\mathrm{Supp}}M,{\mathrm{Supp}}N\subseteq\Phi$ implies ${\mathrm{Supp}}X\subseteq\Phi$.
Definition 5.1. Define $A\sim B$ if and only if $\overline{C(A)}=\overline{C(B)}$, i.e. they generate the same nullity class.
Definition 5.1. The linearization of $F\colon\mathcal{B}\rightsquigarrow\mathcal{A}$ is the functor $D_{1}F\colon\mathcal{B}\rightsquigarrow\mathcal{A}$ given as the explicit chain complex $(D_{1}F_{*},\partial_{*})$ where: $(D_{1}F)_{k}\mathrel{:=}\begin{cases}C_{2}^{\times k}F&k\geq 1\\ \mathrm{cr}_{1}F&k=0\\ 0&\text{otherwise}.\end{cases}$ The chain differential $\partial_{1}\colon(D_{1}F)_{1}\to(D_{1}F)_{0}$ is given by the map $\rho_{1}$ of 4.6, and the chain differential $\partial_{k}\colon(D_{1}F)_{k}\to(D_{1}F)_{k-1}$ is given by $\sum_{i=1}^{k}(-1)^{i}C_{2}^{\times i}\epsilon$ when $k\geq 1$.
Definition 3.2. There is a (large) category4It is more categorically natural to describe the Kleisli bicategory for the pseudomonad $\textup{{Ch}}(-)$ acting on the 2-category of abelian categories, functors, and natural transformations. The category $\textup{{AbCat}}_{\textup{{Ch}}}$ is then the quotient 1-category whose morphisms are isomorphism classes of parallel 1-cells. While it is somewhat inelegant to define the morphisms in a 1-category to be isomorphism class of functors, much of our work actually takes place in a further quotient of $\textup{{AbCat}}_{\textup{{Ch}}}$ where naturally chain homotopically equivalent functors are identified; see Definition 3.5. $\textup{{AbCat}}_{\textup{{Ch}}}$ whose: • objects are abelian categories; • morphisms $\mathcal{B}\rightsquigarrow\mathcal{A}$ are natural isomorphism classes of functors $\mathcal{B}\to\textup{{Ch}}\mathcal{A}$; • identity morphisms $\mathcal{A}\rightsquigarrow\mathcal{A}$ are the functors $\textup{deg}_{0}\colon\mathcal{A}\to\textup{{Ch}}\mathcal{A}$; and in which • composition of morphisms $\mathcal{C}\rightsquigarrow\mathcal{B}$ and $\mathcal{B}\rightsquigarrow\mathcal{A}$, corresponding to the pair of functors $G\colon\mathcal{C}\to\textup{{Ch}}\mathcal{B}$ and $F\colon\mathcal{B}\to\textup{{Ch}}\mathcal{A}$, is defined by $\xymatrix{F\circ G:\mathcal{C}\ar[r]^{\quad G}&\textup{{Ch}}\mathcal{B}\ar[r]^% {\textup{{Ch}}F\ }&\textup{{Ch}}\textup{{Ch}}\mathcal{A}\ar[r]^{\mathrm{Tot}}&% \textup{{Ch}}\mathcal{A}}$ Note that AbCat defines a subcategory of $\textup{{AbCat}}_{\textup{{Ch}}}$, where a functor $F\colon\mathcal{B}\to\mathcal{A}$ is identified with the morphism $\mathcal{B}\rightsquigarrow\mathcal{A}$ in $\textup{{AbCat}}_{\textup{{Ch}}}$ represented by the functor $\xymatrix{\mathcal{B}\ar[r]^{F}&\mathcal{A}\ar[r]^{\textup{deg}_{0}\ }&\textup% {{Ch}}\mathcal{A}}$
